WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:22.590 --> 00:00:24.460
&gt;&gt; Anne E. McLean: Good evening.

00:00:24.460 --> 00:00:27.100
I'm Anne McLean from the
library's music division.

00:00:27.100 --> 00:00:29.420
Tonight we are very
pleased to presenting --

00:00:29.420 --> 00:00:31.510
to be presenting the first

00:00:31.510 --> 00:00:34.760
of two concerts features
the musicians from Marlboro.

00:00:34.760 --> 00:00:38.070
And as you'll hear in a
conversation, the Marlboro Festival

00:00:38.070 --> 00:00:40.910
and its extraordinary
musicians are very much a part

00:00:40.910 --> 00:00:43.910
of our concert history here
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:43.910 --> 00:00:47.910
With these two concerts, we're
celebrating the 65th anniversary

00:00:47.910 --> 00:00:52.200
of the festival, founded in 1951
by legendary artist presented here

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:55.910
in the Coolidge many, many
times in the past century.

00:00:55.910 --> 00:01:00.140
Adolf Busch and his brother Hermann
Busch, Rudolf Serkin, Marcel Moyse

00:01:00.140 --> 00:01:06.040
and his wife, Blanche Honegger
Moyse and their son, Louis.

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:09.070 position:56%
And I'd like to introduce three
wonderful artists who are continuing

00:01:09.070 --> 00:01:12.600 position:56%
to Marlboro tradition, cellist Marcy
Rosen, who's appeared her a number

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:18.520
of times and violinist, David
McCarroll and Emilie-Anne Gendron.

00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:21.760
Also with us is a good friend
and colleague, Michael Wilpers,

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:24.320
who is a performing arts
programmer for the Bill

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:26.480
and Mary Meyer Concert Series

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:30.140
at the Smithsonian's Freer
and Sackler Galleries.

00:01:30.140 --> 00:01:34.110 position:56%
We are really delighted that Michael
had been very interested with us

00:01:34.110 --> 00:01:36.300
in the idea of a joint presentation

00:01:36.300 --> 00:01:38.310
for the Marlboro concerts
this season,

00:01:38.310 --> 00:01:42.100
which has a particular resonance
for our 90th anniversary.

00:01:42.100 --> 00:01:45.880
We had the idea to join forces
this very informal talk,

00:01:45.880 --> 00:01:48.910
inspired by all the warm
relationships that grew

00:01:48.910 --> 00:01:51.390
out of the founding artist
friendships and connections.

00:01:51.390 --> 00:01:56.080 position:56%
And we'd like to talk about how so
many Marlboro influences have helped

00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:59.120
to shape the practice and the
performance of chamber music

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:02.270
over the past six and
a half decades.

00:02:02.270 --> 00:02:05.810
In fact, that story of
Marlboro is really the story

00:02:05.810 --> 00:02:07.650
of chamber music in America.

00:02:07.650 --> 00:02:12.390
Something the library and the Freer
both have a long perspective on.

00:02:12.390 --> 00:02:14.650
And both our organizations
have been a part

00:02:14.650 --> 00:02:16.970
of that story since its beginning.

00:02:16.970 --> 00:02:20.330
The first concert sponsored here
in Washington by our founder,

00:02:20.330 --> 00:02:22.120
Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge,
were presented

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:27.130
at the Freer in February 1924.

00:02:27.130 --> 00:02:29.210
Before we look at some
of this history,

00:02:29.210 --> 00:02:34.110
including the American debut by
Serkin and Busch here in 1933,

00:02:34.110 --> 00:02:37.120
we wanted to talk with the artists
and set the scene a little bit

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:42.320
about the current Marlboro life
and talk about your experience.

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:45.320
Michael, you had a
question on this for them.

00:02:46.950 --> 00:02:48.570
&gt;&gt; Michael Wilpers: Well, one
of the things, I had a chance

00:02:48.570 --> 00:02:52.960
to visit Marlboro finally a couple
summers ago and I discovered

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:58.850
that for me, it felt so much more
like a retreat than a festival

00:02:58.850 --> 00:03:02.680
in the conventional sense
because it's so far away

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:06.350
out in the mountains and the woods.

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:10.040
And it -- what came to life for
me were quotes I had already read

00:03:10.040 --> 00:03:13.240
on the anniversaries of Marlboro
by so many of the artists --

00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:16.670
was the unique opportunity
for some of the young artists,

00:03:16.670 --> 00:03:21.700
not knowing how unique it was, to
spend very extended lengths of time

00:03:21.700 --> 00:03:24.540
on individual pieces in rehearsal.

00:03:24.540 --> 00:03:29.340
There's often reiterated quote
in some of the literature

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:32.220
by a young artist who went
to Marlboro and thought,

00:03:32.220 --> 00:03:34.050
"I've made the right
career decision.

00:03:34.050 --> 00:03:36.720
This is wonderful, we get to work
on pieces for weeks and weeks

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:39.590
and then perform them in public,
only when they're perfect."

00:03:39.590 --> 00:03:43.770
And only after leaving Marlboro
and then finally launching

00:03:43.770 --> 00:03:47.620
onto a music career, getting
invited to a symphony orchestra

00:03:47.620 --> 00:03:50.610
to play a concerto, found out
that he gets one rehearsal

00:03:50.610 --> 00:03:52.520
and then we go onstage.

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:56.000
And this was somewhat of a
crushing disappointment and a slap

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.190
of reality, but it's -- everyone
at Marlboro speaks about the --

00:04:01.190 --> 00:04:04.920
the richness in interpretation
and insight into a piece,

00:04:04.920 --> 00:04:07.800 position:56%
shared insight perfection of a piece

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:10.140
through all the time that's
spent together on them.

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:14.900
So I was hoping that each of you
might reflect on some of the ways

00:04:14.900 --> 00:04:16.640
of which that much time on a piece

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:21.340
with such great musicians has
created memorable insights

00:04:21.340 --> 00:04:26.050
and routinely gives you a
much, much deeper knowledge

00:04:26.050 --> 00:04:28.530
and awareness of a piece.

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:29.870
&gt;&gt; Marcy Rosen: Well,
I guess I'll start.

00:04:29.870 --> 00:04:31.900
First of all, nothing's
ever perfect.

00:04:31.900 --> 00:04:38.210
But we do have an incredible
luxury of time to spend there

00:04:38.210 --> 00:04:43.530
and through -- when you -- and I
have a saying that I like to say,

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:45.710
which is that when you
learn something at Marlboro,

00:04:45.710 --> 00:04:47.770
you know it for your lifetime.

00:04:47.770 --> 00:04:50.960
And that's true of any piece
that I worked on there as a --

00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:55.280
as a student starting
back many years ago.

00:04:55.280 --> 00:05:00.180
And the things and the pieces
that I've explored in the time

00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:03.270
that I've come back and
been one of the old people,

00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:05.640
it's been really incredible.

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:08.810
David and I have spent a
lot of time together there.

00:05:08.810 --> 00:05:13.640
We have the luxury of working on
two of Beethoven's late quartets,

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:17.590 position:56%
the Opus 130 with the fugue and then
the next summer we did Opus 131.

00:05:17.590 --> 00:05:20.840
And we spent seven weeks
on each of those pieces

00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:25.080
and we had an incredible time
exploring that and learning that,

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:28.910
and being inspired not just
by our own work with it,

00:05:28.910 --> 00:05:32.730
but by input that we got from other
people that were at the festival,

00:05:32.730 --> 00:05:34.530
like Michael Tree and
Arnold Steinhardt.

00:05:34.530 --> 00:05:38.800
And so we had great lessons
with those people and I think

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:43.200
that the idea of sharing ideas
is what Marlboro is really about,

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:46.880
also learning how to
vocalize your own ideas.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:49.980
And I think that's
really the main gift

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:53.250
that we're given at
-- at the festival.

00:05:53.250 --> 00:05:56.930
And so, it's -- it is called
a festival, it is a retreat,

00:05:56.930 --> 00:06:01.430
we all live together, we all eat
together, we all get crazy together

00:06:01.430 --> 00:06:04.190
and we all get really
grumpy together, a few.

00:06:04.190 --> 00:06:07.780
So everybody -- you have to learn
to live with the moods and you --

00:06:07.780 --> 00:06:12.090
and live in close quarters and now
we have the outlets of computers

00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:16.080 position:56%
and cell phones, which when I was
there as a kid, we didn't have that.

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:20.440
There was one payphone in each dorm
and I -- we used to write letters.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:21.970
Remember how we used
to write letters?

00:06:21.970 --> 00:06:26.300
Yeah, such a luxury, that's also
something that we don't do anymore,

00:06:26.300 --> 00:06:33.810
but it's a -- it's a great place to
-- to be nurtured in a musical way.

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:38.110
&gt;&gt; David McCarroll: As
Marcy said everything

00:06:38.110 --> 00:06:39.410
so beautifully, it's hard to add.

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:41.310
But one thing I would
add is just the --

00:06:41.310 --> 00:06:44.700
the place itself, the nature I
think is very important to it,

00:06:44.700 --> 00:06:49.420
that it's not -- you don't
realize the hectic pace of life

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:53.430 position:56%
that you know is going on, you know,
for seven weeks at the same time,

00:06:53.430 --> 00:06:55.650
but you're just so
far away from that.

00:06:55.650 --> 00:06:59.140
And that, you know, I often think
about this, that life is sort

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:01.150
of getting a, you know,
faster and faster pace,

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:03.170
almost uncontrollably so.

00:07:03.170 --> 00:07:08.670
And it's just -- obviously when it
was founded 65 years ago, probably,

00:07:08.670 --> 00:07:13.380
you know, Serkin could
never even imagined how --

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:17.550
how valuable it is today to
have seven weeks just away

00:07:17.550 --> 00:07:19.380
from everything, just
to focus on music.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:25.100
You don't even have to worry
about food or anything, you --

00:07:25.100 --> 00:07:29.250
you know, get up in the morning,
you walk to rehearsal, you have --

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:32.440
have meals with your colleagues
and friends and then you go back

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:35.950
to rehearsing and this just happens
over and over for seven weeks.

00:07:35.950 --> 00:07:41.530 position:56%
And so, inevitably something special
comes out of that -- that process.

00:07:41.530 --> 00:07:45.600 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Emilie-Anne Gendron: Yeah, I
mean, all these things I fully agree

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:50.690
with and yeah, the only thing
I guess I could add is --

00:07:50.690 --> 00:07:52.600
well, I guess a couple things.

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:55.930
First of all, Michael,
you mentioned the --

00:07:55.930 --> 00:07:58.900
the hypothetical case
of the young person

00:07:58.900 --> 00:08:02.780
who has the slap in
the face of reality.

00:08:02.780 --> 00:08:06.670
And, you know, after having spent
such luxury of time of working

00:08:06.670 --> 00:08:09.710
on pieces and, it's
funny, I think about that

00:08:09.710 --> 00:08:12.560
because my experience coming
to Marlboro was actually kind

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:16.050
of the opposite of that
because I was sort of --

00:08:16.050 --> 00:08:18.500
well, my time at Marlboro was spent

00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:20.750
like in my -- my late
20's basically.

00:08:20.750 --> 00:08:24.870
So I'd already sort of been out
of school and, you know, working

00:08:24.870 --> 00:08:30.690
and doing concerts and, you know,
I -- by the time I was at Marlboro,

00:08:30.690 --> 00:08:35.090
like in my daily life during
the year, I knew pretty well how

00:08:35.090 --> 00:08:38.350
to put something together
pretty quickly and to, you know,

00:08:38.350 --> 00:08:42.540
create the illusion that I knew
it as well as I possibly did.

00:08:42.540 --> 00:08:45.920
But -- but it was actually
kind of an enlightening

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:49.360 position:56%
and completely shattering experience
for me to have these years --

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:53.180
these summers at Marlboro where
I didn't have to feel that,

00:08:53.180 --> 00:08:56.420
like I was constantly under
the gun of having to, you know,

00:08:56.420 --> 00:08:58.430
put something together
really quickly and just sort

00:08:58.430 --> 00:09:00.090
of like make the product.

00:09:00.090 --> 00:09:04.270
It -- it wasn't about that, it
was really just about the exchange

00:09:04.270 --> 00:09:08.430
of these ideas and how to
vocalize them, as Marcy said.

00:09:08.430 --> 00:09:14.030 position:56%
And, you know -- yeah, the luxury of
time, it really taught me something

00:09:14.030 --> 00:09:20.760
about what it means to approach
music just -- not as a vocation,

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:24.250
but as a thinking musician
who, you know,

00:09:24.250 --> 00:09:26.210
lives these pieces
time and time again.

00:09:26.210 --> 00:09:32.240 position:56%
And that's actually one of the big
privileges of having pieces selected

00:09:32.240 --> 00:09:36.050
for these musicians from
Marlboro tours that, you know,

00:09:36.050 --> 00:09:40.970
we had the luxury of spending
such time on them, so much time,

00:09:40.970 --> 00:09:44.810
you know, in a past summer and
then we have time away from it for,

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:47.780
you know, well, in this
case, like two years.

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:50.660
And then we came back to it and
the insights and the things,

00:09:50.660 --> 00:09:52.980
at least for myself,
that I -- that I --

00:09:52.980 --> 00:09:58.910
that came forth when I sort of
studied it a second time, you know,

00:09:58.910 --> 00:10:03.680
that was also like very
eye-opening to just have --

00:10:03.680 --> 00:10:06.140
yeah, the luxury of time, but
then also time away from it.

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:12.040
And then, I'm speaking specifically
about the Penderecki piece,

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:14.490
which will be featured tonight.

00:10:14.490 --> 00:10:18.850
&gt;&gt; Marcy Rosen: The tours are
always set up around a work

00:10:18.850 --> 00:10:22.620
that gets what supposedly is
an extraordinary performance

00:10:22.620 --> 00:10:25.770
at the festival, so we don't like
to think that we do things that --

00:10:25.770 --> 00:10:27.400
on that level all the time.

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:31.220
But, so we -- we did a nice
performance of the Penderecki

00:10:31.220 --> 00:10:35.710
at Marlboro and Mr. Penderecki
was there and we worked with him.

00:10:35.710 --> 00:10:38.800
And it's a -- actually a really,
incredibly wonderful piece,

00:10:38.800 --> 00:10:40.480
which I know you'll enjoy.

00:10:40.480 --> 00:10:45.180 position:56%
It's very atmospheric, very --
well, Emilie describes it very well.

00:10:45.180 --> 00:10:47.990
She'll -- she'll talk about that
later, but it's a really beautiful

00:10:47.990 --> 00:10:52.180
and very accessible piece
with gorgeous textures

00:10:52.180 --> 00:10:55.010
and colors, so it's moving.

00:10:55.010 --> 00:10:59.950
And I think the program that we
built around it also enhances that,

00:10:59.950 --> 00:11:04.060 position:56%
so the program's -- the program fits
together in a really lovely way.

00:11:04.060 --> 00:11:08.690 position:56%
But actually none of the pieces ends
with a big loud chord, everything --

00:11:08.690 --> 00:11:11.030 position:56%
everything ends softly, so that's --

00:11:11.030 --> 00:11:13.450
that's something actually
-- I actually really like.

00:11:13.450 --> 00:11:15.130
It requires a different attention

00:11:15.130 --> 00:11:18.170
and a different reaction
from -- from all of you.

00:11:18.170 --> 00:11:21.390
&gt;&gt; Michael Wilpers: If I could
follow up with one more question

00:11:21.390 --> 00:11:24.000
about the experience at Marlboro.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:25.820
One thing you learn when
you're visiting there,

00:11:25.820 --> 00:11:30.240
spending time there is
egalitarian philosophy.

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:34.050
There -- there are words
I used when I was there

00:11:34.050 --> 00:11:36.550
that I learned quickly not to use

00:11:36.550 --> 00:11:39.100
and I wish I could
remember what they were.

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:42.620 position:56%
It might have been, you know, master
musician and student or faculty

00:11:42.620 --> 00:11:45.640
and student, certain words like
that, but those are really --

00:11:45.640 --> 00:11:50.260
you leave them at the door,
maybe senior artists' use --

00:11:50.260 --> 00:11:51.910
&gt;&gt; Marcy Rosen: We're called
senior members, but --

00:11:51.910 --> 00:11:53.890
&gt;&gt; Michael Wilpers: --
senior members, yes.

00:11:53.890 --> 00:11:56.540
But I was going to -- what
I was going to get to is

00:11:56.540 --> 00:11:58.400
when you're rehearsing,
you know, [inaudible],

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:02.620 position:56%
many of us have probably seen master
classes where there's no question,

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:07.940 position:56%
in fact, that's the whole point that
the master is putting the student

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:11.530
in their place at many --
in a lot of -- often enough.

00:12:11.530 --> 00:12:15.230
But I wonder if in these long
-- long weeks of rehearsal,

00:12:15.230 --> 00:12:20.190
how you negotiate between the
musicians who have been around

00:12:20.190 --> 00:12:23.710
and played the piece for decades,
and young musicians coming

00:12:23.710 --> 00:12:26.680
in who are extremely talented, but
don't have that depth of experience

00:12:26.680 --> 00:12:32.090
and yet, the ideal is you share
reflections and input equally.

00:12:32.090 --> 00:12:36.530
So I just wonder if you
could tell a few anecdotes

00:12:36.530 --> 00:12:41.030
or make some generalities about
how that plays out over the weeks.

00:12:41.030 --> 00:12:42.780
&gt;&gt; Marcy Rosen: Well, I think
it's -- I mean, I'll speak --

00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:44.080
I can only speak for myself,

00:12:44.080 --> 00:12:46.070
but I think it's different
with each senior.

00:12:46.070 --> 00:12:51.900
I -- you know, everybody runs
their groups a little differently

00:12:51.900 --> 00:12:53.200
and I can tell you in --

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:56.060
in the years that I was
there with what people

00:12:56.060 --> 00:13:00.010 position:56%
that I consider my mentors, I pretty
much did everything they told me

00:13:00.010 --> 00:13:01.620
to do.

00:13:01.620 --> 00:13:05.840
And -- and I really learned from
that and I wanted to do that,

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:09.270
I wanted to hear Felix
Galimir tell me what to do.

00:13:09.270 --> 00:13:13.550
And I wanted to take in his --
and I wanted to soak it up and --

00:13:13.550 --> 00:13:19.810
and in fact, the soaking up of
the knowledge and the education

00:13:19.810 --> 00:13:25.000
that I had from Felix Galimir and
Philipp Naegele and Pina Carmirelli

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.940
and [inaudible] and Rudolf
Serkin and Sasha Schneider

00:13:27.940 --> 00:13:32.530
and Mischa Schneider and all these,
you know, the list is humongous.

00:13:32.530 --> 00:13:35.590
And I was privileged to
get to work with them,

00:13:35.590 --> 00:13:39.080
that's the whole reason I went
back was because I felt I wanted

00:13:39.080 --> 00:13:43.260
to pass their -- I didn't want
their knowledge to die and I wanted

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:44.760
to pass it -- pass it on.

00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:48.450
And so I'm like the next
step to keeping some

00:13:48.450 --> 00:13:49.760
of those traditions alive.

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:53.850
And I want those traditions to be
carried on and so I tried to --

00:13:53.850 --> 00:13:58.690
I don't teach in these things,
but you know, I think just that --

00:13:58.690 --> 00:14:03.720
just sometimes I'll say
something that will inspire people

00:14:03.720 --> 00:14:09.150
or the idea will come out in a
