it creates and the --

00:36:45.370 --> 00:36:48.590 position:56%
the gamut of moods that it explores.

00:36:48.590 --> 00:36:52.410
As many of you may know,
Penderecki -- his --

00:36:52.410 --> 00:36:57.330
Penderecki's music figured into
some of the big film scores

00:36:57.330 --> 00:36:59.560
of the past few decades,

00:36:59.560 --> 00:37:04.500
such as <i>The Shining </i>or
even <i>The Exorcist </i>and --

00:37:04.500 --> 00:37:05.970
and numerous other films.

00:37:05.970 --> 00:37:09.930
He's written -- he sort of made
that leap into pop culture.

00:37:09.930 --> 00:37:12.840
I learned he even has an
asteroid named after him,

00:37:12.840 --> 00:37:15.980
which must be like a great honor.

00:37:15.980 --> 00:37:20.230
But like the thing about --
yeah, I think maybe because he's

00:37:20.230 --> 00:37:26.350
so effective writing for
film is that he's so adept

00:37:26.350 --> 00:37:32.150
at creating just an all
encompassing mood, you know,

00:37:32.150 --> 00:37:33.760
whatever that mood might be.

00:37:33.760 --> 00:37:37.940
And the piece itself is -- it's
quite short, its four movements,

00:37:37.940 --> 00:37:40.530
three of them are attacka
[phonetic], they go consecutively.

00:37:40.530 --> 00:37:47.130
You can't really hear
when they stop and start.

00:37:47.130 --> 00:37:49.620
And each movement is
sort of a tip of the hat,

00:37:49.620 --> 00:37:54.600
in a way to different
composers of the past.

00:37:54.600 --> 00:37:56.440
You can -- you'll see
in your programs,

00:37:56.440 --> 00:37:58.740
the movement titles
are very evocative.

00:37:58.740 --> 00:38:04.560
There's a ironic waltz,
serenade that reminds you

00:38:04.560 --> 00:38:07.620
of something you might hear
in a [inaudible] Schoenberg.

00:38:07.620 --> 00:38:12.040
The last movement, for instance,
is -- entitled Abscheid,

00:38:12.040 --> 00:38:13.760
which means farewell in German.

00:38:13.760 --> 00:38:18.630
That's a very strong Beethoven
[inaudible] reference built in.

00:38:18.630 --> 00:38:24.440
And so, yeah, and as Marcy
said, it really captures some

00:38:24.440 --> 00:38:27.620
of that same sort of
a autumnal feeling

00:38:27.620 --> 00:38:29.500
that you get in the [inaudible].

00:38:29.500 --> 00:38:32.180
It -- they're very similar
and they're kindred spirits

00:38:32.180 --> 00:38:36.660
in many ways, so hopefully this
will enhance your listening of --

00:38:36.660 --> 00:38:39.140
of all the pieces in the program.

